    <chapt>

      <heading>General Manuals</heading>

      <p>
	The following general manuals are available:
	<list compact>
	  <item>
	    <p>Project Manual</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>META Manual</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>FAQ</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Dictionary</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Book Suggestions</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>online magazines</p>
	  </item>
	</list>
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Project Manual</em> explains the history, the
	goals, and related issues about the Debian Project. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>META Manual</em> tells the user where to look
	for the document that covers her/his questions. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>FAQ</em> is a list of questions frequently asked
	by users of a Debian GNU/Linux system and the answers to
	these questions. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Dictionary</em> describes and defines the terms
	used in the Debian manuals. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Book Suggestions</em> is a list of books which
	are intended as suggestions for further reading on
	various topics covered in the Debian manuals. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The Debian GNU/Linux distribution comes with the
	following <em>online magazines</em>: 
	<list compact>
	  <item>
	    <p>Linux Gazette (English)</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>PLUTO Journal (Italian)</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>L'Echo de Linux (French)</p>
	  </item>
	</list>
      </p>
    </chapt>
    <chapt>

      <heading>User Manuals</heading>

      <p>
	The following user manuals are available:
	<list compact>
	  <item>
	    <p>User's Manual</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Tips</p>
	  </item>
	</list>
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>User's Manual</em> covers everything a user should
	know about a Debian GNU/Linux system from a user's view
	point. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Tips</em> is a collection of tips on how to do certain
	things in a Debian GNU/Linux system. 
      </p>

    </chapt>

    <chapt>

      <heading>Administrator Manuals</heading>

      <p>
	The following administrator manuals are available:
	<list compact>
	  <item>
	    <p>Hardware Compatibility List</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Release Notes</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Installation Manual</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>System Administrator's Manual</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Network Administrator's Manual</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Kernel Configuration Manual</p>
	  </item>
	</list>
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Hardware Compatibility List</em> lists all pieces of
	hardware known to work or not to work with the Debian
	GNU/Linux distribution.  This list also includes hints to set
	up Debian to work for a certain piece of hardware, e.g. sample
	X configurations for different display adapters. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Release Notes</em> describe all release specific
	information of the Debian GNU/Linux distribution. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Installation Manual</em> contains instructions on how
	to install the Debian GNU/Linux distribution. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>System Administrator's Manual</em> covers all system
	administration aspects of a Debian GNU/Linux system. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Network Administrator's Manual</em> covers all network
	administration aspects of a Debian GNU/Linux system. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Kernel Configuration Manual</em> describes all aspects
	of configuring a kernel in a Debian GNU/Linux system. 
      </p>

    </chapt>

    <chapt>

      <heading>Development Manuals</heading>

      <p>
	The following development manuals are available: 
	<list>
	  <item>
	    <p>Developer's Reference</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Policy Manual</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Introduction: Making a Debian Package</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Packaging HOWTO</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Packaging Manual</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>dpkg Intenals Manual</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Menu System Manual</p>
	  </item>
	</list>
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Developer's Reference</em> describes how to contribute
	to the Debian GNU/Linux distribution.  This includes an
	introduction for becoming a new developer, the upload
	procedure, how to handle the bug tracking system, mailing
	lists, Internet server, etc.  This manual is thought as a
	<em>reference manual</em> for all Debian developers, newbies
	as well as oldpros. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Policy Manual</em> describes the policy requirements
	for the Debian GNU/Linux distribution. This includes the
	structure and contents of the Debian archive, several design
	issues of the operating system, as well as technical
	requirements each package must satisfy to be included in the
	distribution. 
      </p>

      <p>
	<em>Introduction: Making a Debian Package</em> gives an
	introduction on how to create a Debian GNU/Linux package. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Packaging HOWTO</em> explains how to create a package
	for the Debian GNU/Linux system.  This manual focusses on
	using <prgn>debmake</prgn>. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Packaging Manual</em> explains how to create a package
	for the Debian GNU/Linux system.  This manual focusses on
	using <prgn>dpkg-dev</prgn>. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>dpkg Internals Manual</em> describes the internals of
	<prgn>dpkg</prgn> and how to write new tools for package
	management using the <prgn>dpkg</prgn> libraries. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Menu System Manual</em> describes the Debian GNU/Linux
	Menu System and the <prgn>menu</prgn> package. 
      </p>

    </chapt>

    <chapt>

      <heading>Documentation Manuals</heading>

      <p>
	The following documentation manuals are available: 
	<list>
	  <item>
	    <p>How to Get Started on a New SGML-based Manual</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Documentation Guidelines</p>
	  </item>
	  <item>
	    <p>Debiandoc-SGML Markup Manual</p>
	  </item>
	</list>
      </p>

      <p>
	<em>How to Get Started on a New SGML-based Manual</em> is an
	example SGML document for Debian.  This example can be used as
	a starting point for people wanting to write a new manual for
	Debian.  It includes an example SGML source code for a manual
	as well as some shell scripts and make scripts to generate the
	different output formats. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Documentation Guidelines</em> is the "Policy Manual"
	for Debian documentation. 
      </p>

      <p>
	The <em>Debiandoc-SGML Markup Manual</em> describes how to use
	the SGML markup commands of the Debiandoc-SGML package. 
      </p>

    </chapt>

